🎯 Objective

Understand how different DAX patterns impact execution in VertiPaq, focusing on:

Storage Engine (SE) vs Formula Engine (FE)

Callback behavior

Query plan shape (number of SE scans)

Iterator vs set-based logic

🧪 Scenario

Model:

Fact table: Sales (~900K rows)

Dimensions: Item, Store, Time, District

Goal:
Compute total sales where:

Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Units] > 2

Grouped by:

Item[Category]
🔴 Version 1 — Iterator + Measure (Inefficient)
TestSlowMeasure :=
SUMX(
    FILTER(Sales, Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Units] > 2),
    [TotalSales]
)
Observations:

Multiple SE queries

CallbackDataID present

Higher FE involvement

Why?

[TotalSales] is evaluated inside an iterator

Requires context transition per row/group

VertiPaq cannot fully execute the measure → callback to Formula Engine

🟡 Version 2 — Iterator + Column (Improved)
TestSlowMeasure :=
SUMX(
    FILTER(Sales, Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Units] > 2),
    Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Dollars]
)
Observations:

Fewer SE queries

Callback reduced or removed

Better performance

Why?

Expression uses a physical column

VertiPaq can aggregate directly

Less need for Formula Engine involvement

🟢 Version 3 — CALCULATE + Measure (Optimized)
TestSlowMeasure :=
CALCULATE(
    [TotalSales],
    Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Units] > 2
)
Observations:

Single SE query

No callback

Clean xmSQL

Best performance

xmSQL Shape:
SELECT
    Item[Category],
    SUM(Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Dollars]),
    SUM(Sales[Sum_Markdown_Sales_Dollars])
FROM Sales
LEFT JOIN Item
    ON Sales[ItemID] = Item[ItemID]
WHERE Sales[Sum_Regular_Sales_Units] > 2
Why?

Filter applied as Boolean predicate

[TotalSales] is simple and can be inlined

Entire query executed in Storage Engine

🔍 Key Learnings
1. Callback = Warning Signal

Appears when VertiPaq cannot execute logic natively

Indicates Formula Engine intervention

CallbackDataID(...) → FE is doing part of the work
2. Measures Inside Iterators Are Risky

May trigger callbacks

Especially when measure logic is not fully pushable

3. Not All Measures Are Equal

Simple measures (e.g., SUM(column)) can be inlined

Complex measures may force callbacks

4. CALCULATE Enables Pushdown

Boolean filters → pushed to Storage Engine

Avoids row-by-row evaluation

Promotes set-based execution

5. Goal: Single SE Scan

Best-performing queries usually:

Have 1 SE query

No callbacks

Minimal FE time

Use simple aggregations over physical columns

🧠 Final Conclusion

When filters are expressed as Boolean conditions and measures can be reduced to simple column aggregations, the engine can execute the entire query in a single Storage Engine scan without callbacks.

🚀 Practical Rule

Prefer:

CALCULATE(
    SUM(Fact[Column]),
    Fact[Condition] = value
)

Avoid when possible:

SUMX(
    FILTER(Fact, condition),
    [Measure]
)
🧩 Takeaway

This exercise shows that performance is not about syntax—it’s about how the engine executes the query.

Understanding:

when VertiPaq can do the work

when the Formula Engine is required

is key to writing scalable DAX.
